Nelson/Nelson huntaway
Homonym Number:
Word Class:noun
Sense Number: 1
Definition:a rock sent down a hillside to disturb sheep [ to save running out a dog.]
Origin:[none]
Register:
Register 2:
Flag: Farm Words
Domain:Rural
Region:[none]
See:Taranaki huntaway, Maori huntaway
Pronunciation:
Notes:
Citations
Date: 0/0/1969
Source: Molesworth
Author: MCCASKILL
Vol / Page: 100
Edition:
Quote: These rocks, started on purpose, were known as 'Nelson huntaways' because young men from that district used to come mustering with young, untrained dogs.
Notes:

Date: 0/0/1941
Source: NZ Slang
Author: BAKER
Vol / Page: 59
Edition:
Quote: Also reported is Nelson huntaway, a stone rolled down a hillside to move stock below instead of sending a dog out.
Notes:

Date: 0/0/1951
Source: NZ High Country
Author: MCLEOD
Vol / Page: 42
Edition:
Quote: On the hill, when sheep are sticking far below you, it's sometimes possible to roll a large rock down a steep face and scare them into movement with its crashing and bounding. This is called a "Nelson huntaway" or just a "Nelson."
Notes:

Date: 15/11/1983
Source: NZ Journal of Agriculture
Author:
Vol / Page: 20
Edition:
Quote: You only run a 'Nelson huntaway' when the sheep have defied your dogs and they, in turn, have defied you. "If your best dog's tired and beaten early, all you've got left is heart strain, hoarse voice and a Nelson huntaway." [Nelson]
